  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most of our sellers have thought carefully about price, preparation, and campaign strategy, but will only start thinking about the actual move in the fortnight before settlement. By then, the good removalists are booked, the boxes are everywhere, and the stress of the last two weeks can wipe out the emotional benefit of a strong sale result. It is avoidable. The move is a solvable logistics problem; it just has to be treated as one.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how to approach the practical side of selling a home in Brisbane: when to book a removalist, how to choose one, what to pack when, the common traps specific to Queensland timber homes, and how to handle the gap between the sale settlement and the new home becoming available. None of it is complicated. It does all need to happen on a sensible timeline.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to start booking</h2>
      <p>The rule of thumb: book your removalist the moment you go under contract, and ideally have already had quotes on the shelf before that. Good Brisbane removalists are often booked out four to six weeks in advance, and during peak months (November through February, and again in the school holiday windows of April and July) the best operators can be fully booked eight to ten weeks ahead. If you wait until the week before settlement to start ringing around, you will end up with whoever has a gap, which is not always a reliable signal of quality.</p>

      <p>During the campaign, get two or three quotes from reputable operators. Have them come and inspect the property rather than quoting over the phone: any removalist who will not do a walk-through of a full three bedroom home is quoting blind, and the number they give you is unreliable. The walk-through takes 20 minutes and produces a far more accurate estimate. You also learn a lot about the company from the person they send.</p>

      <p>Once you go under contract, your settlement date gives you a fixed target. Book the removalist for the settlement date itself, or the day after if you have negotiated a day or two of access post-settlement. Do not book them for the day before, even if you feel organised. Last-minute contract variations, settlement delays, or access issues can push everything back, and it is far cheaper to have the removalist stand down than to have 40 boxes of your life sitting in a driveway with nowhere to go.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to choose a removalist (and what to watch for)</h2>
      <p>A good Brisbane removalist will be a member of the Australian Furniture Removers Association (AFRA), carry genuine transit insurance (not just public liability, which is not the same thing), and have experience with the type of property you are moving out of. A team that mostly moves apartment-to-apartment may not be equipped for a three level Queenslander with narrow stairs, high-set verandahs, and heavy timber furniture that needs to come through a tight front door. Ask specifically about similar jobs they have done recently.</p>

      <p>Look at the ratings carefully. Consistent complaints about damaged furniture, late arrivals, or last-minute subcontracting are red flags. Ask whether the crew on the day will be their own employees or subcontractors: reputable operators mostly use their own staff, which means more consistent training, accountability, and care with your belongings. Subcontracting is common at the cheap end of the market and is a significant driver of the horror stories.</p>

      <p>On pricing, expect to pay somewhere in the range of $1,500 to $3,500 for a local Brisbane move of a three to four bedroom home, depending on access, volume, and whether you pack yourself or pay for a full packing service. A quote under $1,200 for a full home move is usually a warning sign. The cost of a move gone wrong (damaged furniture, delayed settlement, extra storage) is always more than the saving you thought you were getting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The packing timeline that actually works</h2>
      <p>Start decluttering the moment you decide to sell, not the moment you go under contract. Everything you genuinely do not want or need is easier to deal with now than it will be at 10pm the night before the move. Op shops, council kerbside collection, marketplace listings, and professional rubbish removal are all faster and cheaper than paying to move items you will throw out within six months anyway.</p>

      <p>Once you are under contract, work backwards from settlement. Six weeks out, pack items you genuinely do not use (books, off-season clothing, decorative items, the garage). Four weeks out, pack the spare rooms. Two weeks out, pack kitchen items you use rarely, the laundry, and anything from the shed or outdoor areas. The final week is for the bulk of the kitchen, bathrooms, and bedrooms. The last 48 hours are for overnight essentials, chargers, and anything you will need immediately at the other end.</p>

      <p>Label everything by destination room (not just contents), and keep a numbered list of boxes so you can quickly identify if anything is missing at the other end. Photograph the back of the TV, the wiring behind the router, and anything else you will have to set up again. This small step saves an extraordinary amount of time and frustration on arrival.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Queensland-specific things to plan for</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's climate and housing stock create a few logistics wrinkles that interstate sellers often underestimate. Older timber homes have tight internal doorways and stairs that can make moving large furniture genuinely difficult. Measure your sofa and your largest wardrobe against your doorways and the stairwell before moving day, not during. If something will not fit, you need to know early so you can either dismantle it, use a craning service, or sell the item before the move.</p>

      <p>The heat also matters. A removal day in summer that starts at 7am is a very different experience from one that starts at 11am. Brisbane can reach 34 degrees by midday in December or January, and boxes, furniture, and people all move more slowly in heat. Ask the removalist to start as early as possible, make sure the teams have access to cold water, and factor in the practical reality that an air-conditioned home being packed up will be hot by lunchtime once the doors have been open all morning.</p>

      <p>If you have pets, arrange for them to be out of the house during the move. Dogs and cats stressed by strangers moving through the home can become genuinely unsafe (both to the removalist crew and to themselves). A morning at a trusted kennel, daycare, or a friend's place is a small cost for a much calmer day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The settlement-day gap</h2>
      <p>One of the most common logistical problems is the gap between settlement on your sale and settlement on your next home. In an ideal world, they are on the same day or one day apart. In reality, they often are not. If you are between homes for more than a few days, you will need short-term accommodation and short-term storage, and both need to be booked in advance.</p>

      <p>Professional removalists will generally offer a storage service for exactly this situation, often at a lower rate than a standalone storage facility because your goods do not need to be re-loaded. If the gap is three days or fewer, this is usually the simplest option. For longer gaps, compare the removalist's storage rate against a dedicated storage facility, which can be cheaper per week but requires a second handling of your goods and all the extra risk of damage that involves.</p>

      <p>For the accommodation side, if you are selling and buying in the same area, short-term apartment rentals or serviced apartments are usually cheaper and more comfortable than hotels for stays of more than a few nights. Book early. In Brisbane's inner east, serviced apartments fill up quickly, particularly during peak move seasons.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do the week of settlement</h2>
      <p>The week before settlement is about finishing the packing and handling the utilities. Electricity, gas, internet, and water all need to be transferred or disconnected, and the new property's services need to be connected. Most providers want 48 to 72 hours of notice for a smooth transition. Do the phone calls on the Monday of settlement week, not the Friday. You also need to redirect mail (Australia Post offers a simple online redirection service), update your address with the bank, super fund, Medicare, and the ATO, and arrange for any regular deliveries to be redirected.</p>

      <p>On settlement day itself, your responsibilities are narrower than most sellers expect. The solicitors handle the actual settlement; your job is to have the property empty, clean, and ready for the buyer to take possession. A thorough final clean (either yourself or through a professional bond clean style service) makes a significant difference to the goodwill of the transaction, particularly if there is any chance of post-settlement contact between you and the buyer. A home left in good condition rarely leads to disputes. A home left in poor condition almost always does.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes to avoid</h2>
      <p>Three mistakes come up regularly. First, underestimating the total time the move will take. A three bedroom home with a garage and a reasonable amount of outdoor equipment is a full day for a three or four person crew. Anything over that, particularly if you have a detached shed, a studio, or a pool area with furniture, will run into a second day. Ask your removalist for an honest estimate, not an optimistic one.</p>

      <p>Second, packing too late. The final 48 hours before a move should be for essentials and last-minute items only. If you are still packing the kitchen at 11pm the night before, you are going to be exhausted on settlement day, and exhausted people make mistakes, forget items, and sign paperwork without reading it carefully. Pace yourself over the six weeks before settlement rather than compressing everything into the final week.</p>

      <p>Third, not protecting valuable or irreplaceable items. Jewellery, important documents, family photos in physical form, and small high-value electronics should travel with you, not on the truck. Removalist insurance covers most scenarios but is not a substitute for keeping the irreplaceable things in your own possession from start to finish.</p>

